    name='search',
    response={
      'result': """CVE-2025-55182, dubbed "React2Shell," is a critical pre-authentication remote code execution (RCE) vulnerability disclosed on December 3, 2025, with a maximum CVSS score of 10.0. This flaw impacts React Server Components (RSC) and any framework leveraging them, including popular ones like Next.js. It specifically affects React versions 19.0.0 through 19.2.0.

The vulnerability stems from insecure deserialization within React's internal "Flight" protocol, which is used to serialize and deserialize "component trees" between the client and server. The server-side decoder in affected React Server Components fails to validate incoming payloads, allowing attackers to inject arbitrary objects. This can lead to server-side prototype pollution and ultimately, the execution of arbitrary code on vulnerable servers without authentication via a single malicious HTTP request.

Exploitation activity related to CVE-2025-55182 was detected as early as December 5, 2025, and it has been added to the CISA KEV (Known Exploited Vulnerabilities) catalog. Public proof-of-concept exploits are readily available and have a near-100% reliability. Attackers have been observed using this vulnerability for initial reconnaissance, fingerprinting compromised systems, verifying privilege levels, mapping network interfaces, enumerating sensitive credentials, and retrieving malicious binaries, including coin miners and Mirai loaders. Both Windows and Linux environments have been observed to be impacted.

Mitigation strategies include rapid patching of affected systems. Google Cloud has rolled out a new Cloud Armor web application firewall (WAF) rule to detect and block exploitation attempts, and platform-level protections are being enforced across App Engine Standard, Cloud Functions, and Cloud Run. Microsoft Defender for Endpoint has also expanded its detection framework to identify and alert on CVE-2025-55182 activity, integrating with automatic attack disruption. It's important to note that while Next.js initially tracked a related vulnerability as CVE-2025-66478, it was later merged into CVE-2025-55182."""
    }
  )
), Part(
